        "category": "Presentation Media Tips",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "tile",
            "title": "\ud83c\udf9e\ufe0f How to Extract and Save GIFs from PowerPoint or Google Slides",
            "steps": [
              {
                "label": "From PowerPoint (PPTX file)",
                "code": "1. Open the `.pptx` file in PowerPoint and **enable editing**.\n2. Navigate to the slide containing the GIF.\n3. Select the GIF and press `Ctrl + C` to copy it.\n4. Open a **new blank PowerPoint presentation** and paste it (`Ctrl + V`).\n5. Go to `File \u2192 Export \u2192 Create an Animated GIF`.\n6. Choose quality, set **duration** (match the actual GIF length), and export."
              },
              {
                "label": "From Google Slides",
                "code": "1. Go to `File \u2192 Download \u2192 Microsoft PowerPoint (.pptx)`.\n2. Open the downloaded file in PowerPoint.\n3. Follow the same steps above to extract the GIF via a new blank presentation."
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "list",
            "text": "Always use a new PowerPoint presentation to export the GIF to avoid formatting or layout issues."
          },
          {
            "type": "list",
            "text": "When exporting, make sure to match the GIF's playback duration under slide timing."
          }
        ]
      }
